In the lifecycle of a Spring Boot application, unit tests and slice tests (@WebMvcTest, @DataJpaTest) are your first line of defense. They are fast, deterministic, and excellent for validating localized business logic.
But isolated tests suffer from a fatal flaw: they validate assumptions, not realities. Your slice tests assume the database handles a specific constraint perfectly. They assume your enterprise event broker will instantly deliver a transaction event. They assume downstream REST dependencies will always match your mocked payloads.
An End-to-End (E2E) test blows away the safety net of mocks. It spins up the entire application context, binds to actual network ports, connects to real databases, and triggers the system exactly the way a client or a message broker would. Here is a practical look at building reliable, maintainable E2E testing pipelines in Spring Boot.
1. The Core Foundation: @SpringBootTest
The cornerstone of Spring Boot integration and E2E testing is the @SpringBootTest annotation. For a true E2E test, you must instruct Spring to bootstrap a real embedded web server rather than using a mocked servlet environment.
Java
@SpringBootTest(webEnvironment = SpringBootTest.WebEnvironment.RANDOM_PORT)
@ActiveProfiles("e2e")
public abstract class BaseE2ETest {
// Shared testing infrastructure goes here
}Why RANDOM_PORT?
Never use DEFINED_PORT (like 8080) in your test suites. If your Continuous Integration (CI) pipeline runs multiple build jobs concurrently on the same runner, fixed ports will collide, causing intermittent, highly frustrating build failures. RANDOM_PORT instructs Spring Boot to look for any available socket on the host machine.
2. Managing External Infrastructure with Testcontainers
The biggest obstacle to writing genuine E2E tests is managing external infrastructure (databases, message brokers, caching layers). Historically, teams relied on shared, static “test environments,” which inevitably became corrupted, out of sync, or bottlenecked.
The modern industry standard to solve this is Testcontainers. Testcontainers allows you to use lightweight, throwaway instances of common databases or queues wrapped in Docker containers directly from your JUnit lifecycle.
Example: E2E Test with a Real Database and Event Broker
Imagine an order processing service that exposes a REST endpoint, saves data to a PostgreSQL instance, and publishes an event.
Java
import io.restassured.RestAssured;
import io.restassured.http.ContentType;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.BeforeEach;
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import org.springframework.boot.test.context.SpringBootTest;
import org.springframework.boot.test.web.server.LocalServerPort;
import org.springframework.test.context.DynamicPropertyRegistry;
import org.springframework.test.context.DynamicPropertySource;
import org.testcontainers.containers.PostgreSQLContainer;
import org.testcontainers.junit.jupiter.Container;
import org.testcontainers.junit.jupiter.Testcontainers;import static io.restassured.RestAssured.given;
import static org.hamcrest.Matchers.equalTo;
@Testcontainers
@SpringBootTest(webEnvironment = SpringBootTest.WebEnvironment.RANDOM_PORT)
class OrderE2ETest {
@LocalServerPort
private int port;
// 1. Define the Docker container infrastructure
@Container
static PostgreSQLContainer<?> postgres = new PostgreSQLContainer<>("postgres:16-alpine");
// 2. Dynamically inject the container's random ports into Spring properties
@DynamicPropertySource
static void configureProperties(DynamicPropertyRegistry registry) {
registry.add("spring.datasource.url", postgres::getJdbcUrl);
registry.add("spring.datasource.username", postgres::getUsername);
registry.add("spring.datasource.password", postgres::getPassword);
}
@BeforeEach
void setUp() {
RestAssured.port = port;
}
@Test
void shouldCreateOrderAndReturnSuccess() {
String requestBody = """
{
"userId": "user-123",
"amount": 99.99
}
""";
// 3. Make an actual network HTTP call using RestAssured
given()
.contentType(ContentType.JSON)
.body(requestBody)
.when()
.post("/api/orders")
.then()
.statusCode(201)
.body("status", equalTo("ACCEPTED"))
.body("userId", equalTo("user-123"));
// 4. (Optional) Verify side effects directly in the DB or downstream queue
}
}
The Power of @DynamicPropertySource
Because Testcontainers maps your database container to a random host port to prevent conflicts, you cannot hardcode values in application-e2e.properties. The @DynamicPropertySource annotation executes before the Spring application context starts, letting you grab the runtime connection strings from the live container and feed them directly into Spring's environment.
3. Handling Downstream Third-Party APIs with WireMock
True E2E testing means testing your application’s behavior when its dependencies respond. However, you rarely want your test suites making live network calls to third-party providers (like Stripe for payments or Twilio for SMS) due to rate-limiting, cost, and instability.
To maintain network-level fidelity without hitting the open internet, use WireMock. WireMock spins up a local HTTP server that intercepts outward calls from your application’s HTTP clients (like RestClient or WebClient) and returns exact, pre-configured HTTP raw responses.
Java
// Configuring WireMock to intercept external inventory partner calls
WireMockServer wireMockServer = new WireMockServer(WireMockConfiguration.wireMockConfig().dynamicPort());
wireMockServer.start();
// Stub a slow network response to test your resilience/timeout logic
wireMockServer.stubFor(get(urlEqualTo("/inventory/item-789"))
.willReturn(aResponse()
.withStatus(200)
.withHeader("Content-Type", "application/json")
.withBody("{\"available\": true}")
.withFixedDelay(2000))); // 2-second network latency simulationWhile powerful, poorly written E2E tests are notorious for destroying build pipelines. Watch out for these traps:Trap 1: Flaky Asynchronous Assertions
If your system relies on event brokers or asynchronous background processing (@Async), an operation might take 50ms or 500ms to settle depending on CI runner CPU load. Never use Thread.sleep() to wait for async operations to finish. It slows down your builds artificially and still flakes when resources are constrained.
Instead, use libraries like Awaitility:
Java
// Awaitility polls dynamically until the condition is met or times out
Awaitility.await()
.atMost(Duration.ofSeconds(5))
.until(() -> orderRepository.count() == 1);Trap 2: Dirty State Pollution
E2E tests mutate state. If TestA inserts a user with the username "johndoe", TestB might fail if it attempts to do the same.

• Avoid wrapping entire E2E tests in @Transactional to roll back state; it can mask threading bugs or hide transaction commit exceptions that only happen in production.

• Instead, write an explicit cleanup mechanism in a @AfterEach method or ensure your test data generation utilizes completely unique UUIDs for each execution run.
Summary: Designing the Test Pyramid
End-to-End testing gives you the ultimate peace of mind that your Spring Boot application will actually bootstrap, connect, and function flawlessly in production. However, because they boot real web containers and spin up real Docker images, they are inherently slower than unit tests.
Reserve your E2E suite for your core business flows — the critical paths that keep the lights on. For everything else, rely on slice and unit tests to keep your inner loop developer experience fast and agile.
